The scattering absorbance model is given by
$$A_{s}=C rac{r^{3}}{\lambda^{4}},$$
and the wavelength–wavenumber relation is
$$\lambda= rac{1}{	ilde{
u}}.$$
Substituting $\lambda=1/	ilde{
u}$ into $A_{s}$ gives
$$A_{s}(	ilde{
u})=C\,r^{3}\,	ilde{
u}^{4}.$$
The absorbance tilt over the spectral range is
$$\Delta A_{s}=A_{s}(	ilde{
u}_{high})-A_{s}(	ilde{
u}_{low})=C\,r^{3}\left(	ilde{
u}_{high}^{4}-	ilde{
u}_{low}^{4}ight).$$
For Pellet 1 and Pellet 2, with identical $C$, $	ilde{
u}_{high}$, and $	ilde{
u}_{low}$, the ratio of tilts is
$$ rac{\Delta A_{s,1}}{\Delta A_{s,2}}= rac{C\,r_{1}^{3}\left(	ilde{
u}_{high}^{4}-	ilde{
u}_{low}^{4}ight)}{C\,r_{2}^{3}\left(	ilde{
u}_{high}^{4}-	ilde{
u}_{low}^{4}ight)}=\left( rac{r_{1}}{r_{2}}ight)^{3}.$$
Given $r_{2}=r_{1}/5$, we have
$$\left( rac{r_{1}}{r_{2}}ight)^{3}=\left( rac{r_{1}}{r_{1}/5}ight)^{3}=5^{3}=125.$$
Thus, the absorbance tilt of Pellet 1 is larger by a factor of $125$ compared to Pellet 2.
